INFLUENZA UPDATE - ASIA
***********************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>

China (Hong Kong)
--------------------
Date: Thu, 28 Jan 1999 01:39:42 +0800
From: Chan Yow Cheong <chanyowcheong@pacific.net.sg>
ProMED-mail Regional Moderator for Asia
Source: Government of Hong Kong Special Administrative Region Department of
Health. Wed 27 Jan 1999 [edited]

In the first three weeks of [Jan 1999], the rates of influenza-like illness
per 1,000 consultations reported by General Out-patient Clinics ranged from
4.2 cases for the week ending 2 Jan; 5.5 cases for the week ending 9 Jan;
and 7.7 cases for the week ending 16 Jan. The preliminary figure for the
week ending 23 Jan is 11.8 cases.
The same rising trend is also noted in the sentinel centres made up of
general practitioners. The rates of influenza-like illness per 1,000
consultations reported by general practitioners are 45.5 cases for the week
ending 2 Jan; 56 cases for the week ending 9 Jan; and 62.2 cases for the
week ending 16 Jan. The preliminary figure for the week ending 23 Jan is
102.8 cases.
February and March is the usual peak season for influenza in Hong Kong each
year. Increased traffic with other countries during the long Chinese New
Year holiday could make Hong Kong more susceptible to the spread of
influenza.
The [Department of Health's] surveillance programme on influenza-like
illness also shows that so far the predominant strain affecting Hong Kong
is the influenza A H3N2 Sydney-like strain.
***
Japan
------
Date: Wed, 27 Jan 99 12:54:05 -0800
From: Takahashi, Hiroshi <hat0303@doh.wa.gov>
Source: Japan Times, 27 Jan 1999 [edited]
At least 24 people nationwide have died of influenza-related diseases this
month, according to a survey conducted by Kyodo News.
Of the 24, 20 were elderly people who died of pneumonia or bronchitis at
welfare facilities, including nursing homes in Iwate, Miyagi, Niigata,
Gunma and Saitama prefectures, according to the survey released Wednesday.
The survey found that 11 people, the largest number of flu victims, died in
Miyagi Prefecture.
Comments from the reporter: The Japanese National Infectious Disease
Surveillance Center recently posted a flu surveillance page on their web
site <http://www.idsc.nih.go.jp/>
--
