Singapore
----------
[1]
Date: Thu, 28 Jan 1999 00:29:42 +0800
From: Chan Yow Cheong <chanyowcheong@pacific.net.sg>
ProMED-mail Regional Moderator for Asia
Source: The Straits Times, Wed 27 Jan 1999 [edited]

Doctors in Singapore reported a 20-50 per cent increase in the number of
influenza cases, with patients taking longer to recover.
Eight out of 10 doctors contacted [by their correspondent] confirmed they
were seeing more patients, with some noting that patients took a longer
time [10-14 days] to recover. Most said the increase started two weeks ago.
A doctor with 13 years' experience said she used to see about 50 patients a
day, about half of whom had the flu; she now sees about 100 patients a day,
and 4 out of 5 have the flu.

[2]
Date: Thu, 28 Jan 1999
From: Chan Yow Cheong <chanyowcheong@pacific.net.sg>
ProMED-mail Regional Moderator for Asia
Source: Singapore Ministry of Health, Wednesday, 27 Jan 1999

The Singapore Ministry of Health has issued a press release on the
influenza situation in Singapore. The relevant portion is excerpted below:
"The Ministry of Health has noted an increase in the number of patients
attending government polyclinics with symptoms of high fever, sore throat,
cough and running nose, associated with headache and general muscle aches,
suggestive of an upper respiratory tract infection or influenza.
During the first 3 weeks of this year, the average weekly [patient visits]
with ?flu-like symptoms showed a 14% increase compared to the average
weekly [patient visits] in 1998. Laboratory surveillance has also shown an
increase in the number of positive tests for influenza. The number of cases
tested positive for the influenza virus has also increased five-fold during
this period, compared with the same period last year.
The influenza A virus was responsible for the majority of cases tested
positive so far. The viruses isolated from influenza cases have
corresponded to the circulating viruses reported by the World Health
Organization. No new or unusual viruses have been isolated in Singapore so
far."
--
ProMED-mail
e-mail: promed@usa.healthnet.org
[According to the WHO Weekly Epidemiological Record of 2 October 1998, the
influenza A viruses which circulated between March and September of 1998
were predominantly of the A(H3N2) subtype; in many countries influenza
A(H1N1) viruses were also isolated. Singapore also reported the isolations
of these two influenza A subtypes - Mod.CYC]
